REFERENCE: gets the list of records for all files matching the specified base name.
MODEL: takes a list of file information records and a file name, and returns a list of all the file information records in the input list that correspond to the specified file name, while preserving the order of the elements in the input list.

REFERENCE: reverses a list of any length.
MODEL: takes a list and returns the reverse of that list by recursively processing the list and using an accumulator to store the intermediate results.

REFERENCE: returns the factorial of a given number.
MODEL: calculates the factorial of a given number by recursively calling itself with a decremented input until it reaches the base case of 1, at which point it returns the result of 1.

REFERENCE: transforms the body of a clause into a list of goals.
MODEL: takes a compound term and a list, and decomposes the compound term into a list by recursively processing the compound term until it reaches the last element, at which point it adds the element to the list.

REFERENCE: succeeds if t is a valid binary tree with integer keys.
MODEL: checks whether a given term is a valid binary search tree by ensuring that it is either the atom nil, or a compound term with an integer key, a non-variable value, and valid left and right sub-trees.

REFERENCE: a set of witnesses have inconsistent testimony if two pieces of testimony belonging to two different witnesses are inconsistent.
MODEL: checks whether a given list of people (w) contains any pairs of people whose testimonies are inconsistent with each other, by using member/2 to check each person in the list and inconsistent/2 to check whether their testimonies are inconsistent.

REFERENCE: valuates the polynomial given the a,b,c,x values.
MODEL: calculates the value of a quadratic equation ax^2 + bx + c at a given value of x (x), given the coefficients a (a), b (b), and c (c), by using is/2 to perform the calculation and bind the result to r.

REFERENCE: takes a list of key-datum pairs (such as keysort could be used to sort) and forms them into a heap.
MODEL: converts a list of key-value pairs into a heap data structure, by recursively adding each element to the heap using add_to_heap/5 and updating the tree and counter variables along the way.

REFERENCE: obtains a socket connection from this node.
MODEL: takes a term representing a socket address (a(hostname, port)) and a stream, and either returns the stream associated with the socket address if it exists and is still open, or creates a new connection to the socket and returns the new stream.

REFERENCE: succeeds if a is the area of shape s.
MODEL: calculates the area of a given shape (s) and returns the result as the second argument (a), where the shape can be either a circle or a box.

REFERENCE: is true when rest contains the elements of set1 except for set1.
MODEL: removes all occurrences of elem from list1, while preserving the order of the elements and returning the result in list2.

REFERENCE: adds a new element with key key and value to the tree t0 creating a new red-black tree tn. duplicated elements are not allowed.
MODEL: takes a tree (tree0), a key (key), a value (val), and a sentinel (nil) as arguments, and inserts a new key-value pair into the tree, preserving the red-black tree properties, and returns the resulting tree (tree).

REFERENCE: gets the list of records for all files whose modification time is within the given range.
MODEL: takes a list of file information records (fileinfos), a start date (start), and an end date (end), and returns a sublist of fileinfos containing only the records whose creation date (time) is within the specified date range (i.e., start <= time <= end), while preserving the order of the elements in the input list.

REFERENCE: is true if and only if filterlist is a list containing only the elements of list that satisfy goal.
MODEL: takes a predicate (p) and a list (list) as arguments, and returns a sublist of list containing only the elements that satisfy the predicate, by recursively processing the list and using the call/1 and !/0 predicates to apply the predicate to each element and determine whether to include it in the result.

REFERENCE: succeeds if the item represents a valid circle x,y represents the centrepoint of a circle on an x,y plane r represents the radius of the circle.
MODEL: checks whether the given arguments (x, y, and r) represent a valid circle by ensuring that they are all numbers and that the radius (r) is a positive number.

REFERENCE: reads a word from the user then lists all anagrams.
MODEL: converts the word into a list of characters (list), generates all permutations of the list (result), converts each permutation back into a word (anagram), and writes the permuted word to the output, until the fail/0 predicate is reached, at which point the program terminates.

REFERENCE: generates all subsets of the given set (once each).
MODEL: generate or check whether a given list (subset) is a subset of another list (set).

REFERENCE: transforms a list, possibly holding lists as elements into a flat list by replacing each list with its elements recursively.
MODEL: takes a list (list) and returns a flattened version of the list, where all sublists within list are recursively flattened and the elements are appended to a result list (result) using the append/3 predicate.

REFERENCE: is true when the two arguments represent the same set. since they are assumed to be ordered representations, they must be identical.
MODEL: checks whether the two given sets (set1 and set2) are equal

REFERENCE: delete an element from a list by just not including it when it's found.
MODEL: takes an element (element) and a list (list) as arguments, and returns a new list (result) with all occurrences of element removed from list.
